    visited, starting from the coordinate of the last digit.
    We will do so by using a number line of length 10^5, and seeing if each
    of these coordinates, ending with the last digit, is visited.

    We will begin by placing the piece at coordinate 1, then at coordinate 2, etc.
    If the coordinate is visited, we will return the minimum number of moves
    needed to reach it. Otherwise, we will continue placing the piece until we
    reach the last digit.

    If we cannot reach the last digit, we will place the piece there, and
    start the process again.

    At the end, we will have placed all the pieces at the end, and will have
    reached the last digit.

    At this point, we know that the last digit is visited, so we will now
    move the piece to the coordinate where it was. This can be achieved by
    subtracting 1 from the coordinate, and adding 1 to the position of the
    piece after subtracting the last digit.

    We will repeat this process for all the coordinates, until we reach the
    coordinate where all the pieces are visited.

    The last digit is the coordinate where we should be.

    Note that since the coordinates are visited, we have to subtract 1 from the
    coordinate as well.

    We will calculate the number of moves needed to reach the last digit
    with an O(N) algorithm, where N is the number of pieces.

    Time - O(N)
    Space - O(1)
